{"id": 122230, "published_time": "2023-03-18T14:00:00+00:00", "expires_time": "2023-03-19T14:00:00+00:00", "created_at": "2023-03-18T12:26:37+00:00", "updated_at": "2023-03-18T14:01:30+00:00", "author": "Andy Anderson", "product_type": "forecast", "bottom_line": "<p>Firm and icy surfaces exist in many areas. Some sunny slopes may start to soften as the day warms up, but the gradual warming should not produce enough wet snow for large or widespread wet snow instabilities. Avalanches should remain unlikely today. Still, pay attention to changing conditions and adjust plans accordingly.</p>", "hazard_discussion": "<p><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" title=\"Normal Caution\" src=\"https://www.sierraavalanchecenter.org//sites/default/files/normalcaution.png\" alt=\"Normal Caution\" /></p>\n<h3 style=\"text-align: center;\"><a class=\"lexicon-term\" title=\"Travel with a plan that provides appropriate safety margins and maintains awareness of the conditions and terrain. Continue using group travel techniques that minimize risks like only exposing one person at a time to avalanche terrain and regrouping in safe zones out of avalanche terrain and runout zones. Ensure that all group members are carrying and properly using companion rescue equipment (transceiver, shovel, and probe).\" href=\"https://www.sierraavalanchecenter.org/avalanche-terms/normal-caution\">Normal caution</a></h3>\n<p>Since Tuesday's storm, the snowpack has consolidated and strengthened. In most areas below 9000 ft, thick refrozen rain crusts exist on or near the surface. Above 9000 ft., firm and dense snow exists. Expect widespread firm icy conditions on exposed slopes this morning. Daytime warming should create a shallow layer of softer wet snow on sunny SE-S-SW aspects today, especially below 8500 ft, similar to the thin wet surface layer that formed by midday on Thursday and Friday. These areas may start to refreeze quickly as cloud cover moves into the area this afternoon. The solid overnight refreeze, today's slightly stronger winds, and afternoon cloud cover should prevent deep wet snow or widespread wet snow instabilities from forming. Less sun-exposed slopes will likely remain frozen and firm today.&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>Recent Observations:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"nac-html-li\">Yesterday observers reported some softening on sunny SE-S-SW aspects by midday. Other aspects and shady areas on the southerly aspects remained firm and frozen. Some of the northerly aspects do have a dusting of soft snow on top of the crusts.&nbsp;</li>\n<li class=\"nac-html-li\">Observers reported graupel and surface hoar on the snow surface in many areas yesterday.</li>\n<li class=\"nac-html-li\">A large, widespread <a class=\"nac-html-a\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanche</a> cycle occurred on Tuesday, March 14, during the last storm.&nbsp; Widespread wind and wet <a class=\"nac-html-a\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/snowpack/slab/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A relatively cohesive snowpack layer.\">slab</a>&nbsp;<a class=\"nac-html-a\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow sliding, tumbling, or flowing down an inclined surface.\">avalanches</a> have been reported, with large&nbsp;<a class=\"nac-html-a\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/avalanche/avalanche-problems/avalanche-problem-type/cornice-fall/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"A mass of snow deposited by the wind, often overhanging, and usually near a sharp terrain break such as a ridge. Cornices can break off unexpectedly and should be approached with caution.\">cornice</a>&nbsp;<a class=\"nac-html-a\" href=\"https://avalanche.org/avalanche-encyclopedia/snowpack/snowpack-observations/signs-of-instability-red-flags/collapse-or-whumpf/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\" data-markjs=\"true\" data-tippy-content=\"When the fracture of a lower snow layer causes an upper layer to fall. Also called a whumpf, this is an obvious sign of instability.\">collapses</a> throughout the forecast region.&nbsp; Many of these avalanches were up to size D3 with potentially a size D4.&nbsp; See the <a href=\"https://www.sierraavalanchecenter.org/observations-explorer#/observations/list\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">observation page</a> for more details.</li>\n<li class=\"nac-html-li\">Rain on Tuesday, March 14, went up to 9000' and potentially higher in some areas.</li>\n</ul>", "weather_discussion": null, "announcement": null, "status": "published", "media": [{"id": 1, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/runnels_6415b04d2b78e-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/runnels_6415b04d2b78e-medium.jpg", "original": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/runnels_6415b04d2b78e.jpg", "thumbnail": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/runnels_6415b04d2b78e-thumbnail.jpg"}, "type": "image", "title": "Rain runnels in the snow surface on Andesite Peak.", "caption": "(3/17/2023) <p>Rain runnels in the snow surface on Andesite Peak.</p> Photo: SAC"}, {"id": 2, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/knife-crust_6415b0361fca6-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/knife-crust_6415b0361fca6-medium.jpg", "original": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/knife-crust_6415b0361fca6.jpg", "thumbnail": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/knife-crust_6415b0361fca6-thumbnail.jpg"}, "type": "image", "title": "Knife hard rain crust in the Tragedy Springs area.", "caption": "(3/17/2023) <p>Knife hard rain crust in the Tragedy Springs area.</p> Photo: SAC"}, {"id": 3, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/rimeandrain_6415b031b7349-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/rimeandrain_6415b031b7349-medium.jpg", "original": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/rimeandrain_6415b031b7349.jpg", "thumbnail": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/rimeandrain_6415b031b7349-thumbnail.jpg"}, "type": "image", "title": "Ice and rime on the trees in the Tragedy Springs area.", "caption": "(3/17/2023) <p>Ice and rime on the trees in the Tragedy Springs area.</p> Photo: SAC"}, {"id": 4, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/firm_6415b03d98a5b-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/firm_6415b03d98a5b-medium.jpg", "original": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/firm_6415b03d98a5b.jpg", "thumbnail": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/firm_6415b03d98a5b-thumbnail.jpg"}, "type": "image", "title": "Firm and icy surfaces on the Castle Peak.", "caption": "(3/17/2023) <p>Firm and icy surfaces on the Castle Peak.</p> Photo: SAC"}, {"id": 5, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/sh_6415b0465f4da-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/sh_6415b0465f4da-medium.jpg", "original": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/sh_6415b0465f4da.jpg", "thumbnail": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/sh_6415b0465f4da-thumbnail.jpg"}, "type": "image", "title": "Surface hoar on Maggies Peak", "caption": "(3/17/2023) <p>Surface hoar on Maggies Peak.</p> Photo: Public"}, {"id": 6, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/castle_6415b02ff07ae-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/castle_6415b02ff07ae-medium.jpg", "original": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/castle_6415b02ff07ae.jpg", "thumbnail": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/castle_6415b02ff07ae-thumbnail.jpg"}, "type": "image", "title": "Overview of Castle and Basin Peak", "caption": "(3/17/2023) <p>Overview of Castle and Basin Peak</p> Photo: SAC"}, {"id": 7, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/202303161355-img_20230316_100806495_64146ef264451-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/202303161355-img_20230316_100806495_64146ef264451-medium.jpg", "original": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/202303161355-img_20230316_100806495_64146ef264451.jpg", "thumbnail": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/202303161355-img_20230316_100806495_64146ef264451-thumbnail.jpg"}, "type": "image", "title": null, "caption": "(3/16/2023) <p>Firm conditions on 6 inch thick P hard rain crust at 10 am.&nbsp; Gold Peak, Pole Creek area.</p> Photo: SAC"}, {"id": 8, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cornices_6415b04414dd4-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cornices_6415b04414dd4-medium.jpg", "original": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cornices_6415b04414dd4.jpg", "thumbnail": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cornices_6415b04414dd4-thumbnail.jpg"}, "type": "image", "title": "Sagging and cracking cornices in the Tragedy Springs area. ", "caption": "(3/17/2023) <p>Sagging and cracking cornices in the Tragedy Springs area.&nbsp;</p> Photo: SAC"}, {"id": 9, "url": {"large": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/202303161355-img_20230316_121709708_64146ef2632fd-large.jpg", "medium": "https://avalanche-org-media.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/202303161355-img_20230316_12170